narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I developed a working knowledge of metal machining and the tools involved. I especially learned what kinds of details need to be given specific attention during particular aspects of the fabrication process.
I gained practical and applicable skills in machining and design that will prove useful for the rest of my life.
I gained a confidence in using tools I'd previously found baffling.
I learned how to use the machines in the machine shop, which is extremely useful for my research.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: This course was very engaging because it was project based. It was very easy to learn in this courses environment, and the class size was great.

I really enjoyed how the course was taught and designed. I honestly don't think there's much obvious room for improvement - I came out feeling comfortable in the shop and knowing how to perform a wide range of tasks.
it is a very good class as it is.
Strengths: Friendly environment, collaboration, clear instructions, comprehensive overview of machine shop basics while building an interesting and unique project.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would definitely recommend this course to students from a variety of majors, who want to better understand metal fabrication techniques and would like to gain experience in these areas.

I would absolutely recommend this to students. Even as an undergraduate receiving no credit for taking the course, I loved it and felt it was an incredibly worthwhile course. It's little hard-to-find and unexpected classes like this one that sometimes are the gems of your semester.
It's great if you like machining.
I highly recommend this course to any undergraduate or graduate student pursuing hands-on/experimental employment post-graduation.
